The `Omit` utility type in TypeScript is used to create a new type by excluding one or more properties from an existing type. It is particularly useful when you want to work with a subset of an existing type but need to exclude specific fields.

### Syntax:
```typescript
Omit<Type, Keys>
```

- `Type`: The original type from which properties will be omitted.
- `Keys`: The keys (property names) to exclude from the original type.

### Example:
```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  password: string;
}

type PublicUser = Omit<User, 'password'>;

// PublicUser will be:
// {
//   id: number;
//   name: string;
//   email: string;
// }
```

In this example, the `Omit` utility removes the `password` property from the `User` type, creating a new `PublicUser` type that excludes sensitive information.

### Purpose:
The primary purpose of `Omit` is to simplify type manipulation by allowing developers to exclude specific properties from a type without having to redefine the entire structure manually.
```

